INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (381, 2, '2013-07-27 13:30:18', '2013-07-27 18:30:18', '<strong>Presenting symptoms</strong>

A 38 year-old female sought treatment for pain in the coccyx after total hip joint replacement surgery due to severe arthritis. Prior to surgery, she had been diagnosed with a leg length inequality, so the surgeon used a longer implant to equalize length on the short side. The surgery was a success, but she continued to have burning pain in the coccyx while sitting at work. 

<strong>Evaluation, Clinical Reasoning & Treatment Strategy:</strong>
The coccyx is also known as the tailbone. It is most often damaged in falls where you land on your backside. In this case there was no fall. Postural analysis revealed a leg length inequality, that now was most likely to be functional (muscle imbalance) as opposed to structural (bone length). Consequently, treatment planning had to be inclusive of muscles on the non-surgical hip that might have compensated and/or been strained both before and after the hip replacement. We reviewed seated posture, and discussed discontinuing use of the doughnut cushion that could be causing compression on the gluteus maximus (which may cause trigger points to form). Muscle testing found weak gluteal muscles, and especially the external rotators. 

<strong>Treatment: </strong>
Treatment began trigger points in muscles of the lumbopelvic region that might reproduce pain in the coccyx. The key to solving this case was in finding a trigger point located in the most medial / inferior portion of the gluteus maximus, close to its attachment on the coccyx. Pressure on this attachment site reproduced the burning pain in her coccyx. Quadratus lumborum, the lumbar multifidi, TFL and adductors were all treated bilaterally due to their functional relationship to the pelvis. We also found the iliopsoas to be inhibited and weak.

<strong>Outcomes & Follow-up:</strong>
The patient was recommended to sit just 15-20 minutes at a time and perform self-stretches to hip flexors and extensors throughout the day. She was instructed self-trigger point compression around the coccyx. After six treatments she was pain-free. She was strongly encouraged begin a maintenance program with a functional strength trainer because she was so young when having hip replacement surgery. 
', 'Coccydynia (coccyx pain)', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'coccydynia-coccyx-pain', '', '', '2013-07-27 13:30:18', '2013-07-27 18:30:18', '', 0, 'http://www.360nmt.com/blog/?p=381', 0, 'post', '', 0) ; 
